name: Bangor Maid
description:
Alternative Irish artifacts Series
Damn Fine Print has curated and hand screen-printed an illustrated 'Alternative Irish Artifacts' series celebrating unique Irish gems!

Bangor Maid is a re-imagined poster by Neal McCullough for a long defunct ice cream brand from Bangor in County Down. Growing up in the tail end of the ‘70s you'd see Bangor Maid posters and stickers adorning the windows of every little corner shop around Greater Belfast. By the 80s Bangor Maid was gone, but a lot of the window stickers lived on – yellowing, fading and cracking slowly in the sweetshop windows of County Down.

SPEC
2 colour silk screen 
Limited Edition of 30
Size - frame friendly 8ich X 11 inch
Silk-screened blue and black ink on 250gsm Cyclus recycled card.

Designed by Neal McCullough / http://handdrawncreative.co.uk

name: The Comet Riders
description:
THE COMET RIDERS By Matthew Griffin 
€50 
2 Colour ( white and black ink) 
Screen printed on 290gsm Italian Turchese Card.
400mm X 500mm – ( IKEA Friendly ! )
Limited edition of 30 / numbered and signed by Artist 


Damn Fine Print recently teamed up with illustrator Matthew Griffin to produce a limited screen printed edition of his ‘Comet Riders Series.’ 'The Comet Riders' is one of a series of illustrations inspired by Matthews love of retro science fiction & graphic art, and as huge fans of his style we were so excited to bring it to life with white and black ink! Matt joined us in the studio to sign each two color print. 

Matthew Griffin is an illustrator & designer from Kells, Co.Meath, now living in Ennis. He has worked with advertisers, publishers, designers & animators and these days mainly designs posters and illustrates books. Matthew is an avid fan of animation, film, graphic design, space, music & his family - but not in that order necessarily.  Check out his portfolio at www.matthewjgriffin.com

name: Alan Clarke
description:
Title: The Something of the Something Something

Alan Clarke: "I was speaking recently to esteemed freelance scientist Mr. J. Patrick Hood, who described to me a curious incident:  As most people know, due to having exceedingly fragile bones, Mr. Hood does most of his work suspended in a water filled tank in his workroom, where the effects of gravity on his feeble skeleton are lessened. On one occasion the failure of an essential gimble caused him to become entirely submerged for a period of time. The resulting lack of oxygen to the brain brought about the most vivid hallucinations and philosophical insights. He described 'seeing souls', not just the souls of people but of objects and places. This is an illustration of the soul of Dublin city as described by Mr Hood. I should declare that Artistic Licence has has been given free rein, primarily because of the lack of existence of souls, and Mr. Hood maybe."

Commissioned work can be illustrations for beer mats or creature designs for Doctor Who, while personal work ranges from Sloth themed board games to paintings of Solid Snake.

name: Ursula Celano
description:
Title: Damn fine Dublin - cycling in the city in the summer thinking of love.

Ursula Celano: "I think the cycling scheme is a great example of Dublin at its best.  The bike design creates a very upright riding position which draws the eye to the beautiful riders  - it almost looks like they are posing.  Mostly I am in town with two small children so the stylish cyclists also symbolise lost youth for me.  I love to make designs which celebrate modern Ireland - particularly from a woman's point of view and a chance to focus on a design for my home city has been wonderful."

name: Mr Steve McCarthy
description:
Title: The Big Smoke 

Steve McCarthy: "The smoke stacks at pigeon house are my favourite landmark in Dublin, from a purely aesthetic point of view they're just nice to look at, those colourful chimneys jutting out of the flat sand of the strand. They make me imagine there's a massive engine underneath Dublin, secretly pumping the whole city with energy. Like the duck. Calm on the surface, but always paddling like fuck underneath."

name: Brian Gallagher
description:
Title: Red Door

Brian Gallagher: "The scraperboard process I practice is the reverse from usual mark making. I begin with a black board and gradually remove parts of it’s thin dark surface to reveal the white china clay beneath."

name: Justinas Alisauskas
description:
Title: The Flying Dubliner 

Justinas Alisauskas: "I am an illustration course student.
Digital illustration is one of my favourite media, because it is
limitless. For this particularly piece I’ve used photoshop and a
drawing tablet.
I begin a piece by little sketch. Later it gets some details and it
grows to a concept.
This piece I have called “The Flying Dubliner”.
I know a piece is done when it looks good and gives me great satisfaction.
When my work is going well, I am filled with happiness.
When people see my work, I'd like them to feel the same."

name: Niall McCormack
description:
Title: The Catacombs

The Catacombs was a legendary 1940s late-night drinking spot frequented by Brendan Behan, Patrick Kavanagh, Antony Cronin, John Jordan and JP Donleavy. "Thither would come, most nights, brigades of young intelligentsia, platoons of poets, past and future revolutionaries … and free loaders … No invitation was required, but a large brown bag of bottled stout was obligatory." – John Ryan, Remembering How We Stood
